## 4. PLACEMENT STRATEGY

Where to put error boundaries in the component tree:

```
App (root boundary — catastrophic fallback only)
├── Layout
│   ├── Sidebar (boundary — sidebar errors don't break content)
│   └── Main
│       ├── Page (boundary per route — page errors show page fallback)
│       │   ├── MetricsPanel (boundary — metrics fail independently)
│       │   ├── DataTable (boundary — table errors don't break metrics)
│       │   └── ActivityFeed (boundary — feed errors are isolated)
```

**Rules of thumb:**
- Boundary at every **route/page** level — this is the minimum
- Boundary around every **independently-loadable section** (widget, panel, feed)
- Boundary around any component that renders **user-generated content** or **third-party embeds**
- Do NOT wrap every single leaf component — that's excessive and hides real bugs
- Do NOT put a single boundary at the app root and call it done — that gives users a blank page on any error

---

## 5. RESET ON NAVIGATION

Error boundaries are sticky — once triggered, they stay in error state until reset. Reset them when the user navigates:

**With React Router:**
```tsx
import { useLocation } from 'react-router-dom';

function PageWithBoundary({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const location = useLocation();

  return (
    <ErrorBoundary
      resetKey={location.pathname}
      fallback={<PageErrorFallback onRetry={() => window.location.reload()} />}
    >
      {children}
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}
```

**With Next.js App Router:**
Next.js has built-in `error.tsx` files per route segment. Use them:
```tsx
// app/dashboard/error.tsx
'use client';

export default function DashboardError({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error;
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return <PageErrorFallback onRetry={reset} />;
}
```

---

## 6. ASYNC ERROR BOUNDARIES (SUSPENSE + ERROR BOUNDARY)

For components using React Suspense (lazy loading, streaming), pair Suspense with an error boundary:

```tsx
import { Suspense, lazy } from 'react';

const HeavyChart = lazy(() => import('./HeavyChart'));

function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <ErrorBoundary fallback={<ErrorFallback title="Chart failed to load" />}>
      <Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
        <HeavyChart />
      </Suspense>
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}
```

**Order matters:** ErrorBoundary wraps Suspense, not the other way around. Suspense handles loading; ErrorBoundary handles failure.

---

## 7. LOGGING AND REPORTING

In production, error boundaries should report to an error tracking service:

```tsx
<ErrorBoundary
  onError={(error, errorInfo) => {
    // Send to Sentry, DataDog, LogRocket, etc.
    errorReporter.captureException(error, {
      componentStack: errorInfo.componentStack,
      route: window.location.pathname,
    });
  }}
>
  {children}
</ErrorBoundary>
```

If no error reporting service exists, at minimum `console.error` in development and suppress in production. Never silently swallow errors.
